{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488652"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:51:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:51:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"502"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/502"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.04,0.54,0.13,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"502"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88384"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/502"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"502"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72579"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"435"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1185"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1476"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7380"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29772"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30082"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30195"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/88384"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 71-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset loss of vision in her left eye occurring two hours ago. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes and hypertension. Her medications include gliclazide and captopril. She has no other significant medical history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 76/min, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Visual acuity testing reveals no light perception in the left eye and 6/6 vision in the right eye. Fundoscopic examination of the left eye reveals extensive retinal haemorrhages throughout all quadrants with multiple pale patches (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Central retinal artery occlusion","Retinal detachment","Central retinal vein occlusion","Hypertensive retinopathy","Diabetic retinopathy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic features of ischaemic \u003Cstrong\u003Ecentral retinal vein occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E. The fundoscopic appearance shows the characteristic \u0027blood and thunder\u0027 appearance with extensive retinal haemorrhages and pale patches representing areas of retinal ischaemia. While central retinal vein occlusion can present acutely, the fundoscopic findings suggest this process has been developing over time despite the acute presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral retinal artery occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with sudden painless visual loss and has a distinctly different fundoscopic appearance with retinal whitening and a cherry-red spot at the macula. While the timing would fit with arterial occlusion, the fundoscopic appearance is not consistent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetinal detachment\u003C/strong\u003E classically presents with visual field defects, flashing lights, and floaters. The retina appears elevated and grey on fundoscopy, unlike the haemorrhagic appearance seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertensive retinopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic condition causing arteriolar narrowing, arteriovenous nipping, and flame haemorrhages. It does not cause such extensive haemorrhages or acute visual loss as seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic retinopathy\u003C/strong\u003E develops gradually with microaneurysms, dot and blot haemorrhages, and hard exudates. While it can cause severe visual loss, the pattern of retinopathy is different from the extensive haemorrhages seen in central retinal vein occlusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECentral retinal vein occlusion is more common in older patients and those with vascular risk factors like hypertension and diabetes. Urgent ophthalmology referral is required in ischaemic cases to prevent complications like neovascular glaucoma. Management options include anti-vascular endothelial growth factor injections and laser photocoagulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Central retinal vein occlusion presents with characteristic \u0027blood and thunder\u0027 appearance on fundoscopy.","Risk factors for central retinal vein occlusion include age over 50, hypertension, diabetes, and glaucoma.","Ischaemic central retinal vein occlusion requires urgent treatment to prevent neovascular glaucoma."],"references":["Rehak M, Wiedemann P. Retinal vein thrombosis: pathogenesis and management. J Thromb Haemost. 2010;8(9):1886-1894. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20492457/","McAllister IL. Central retinal vein occlusion: a review. Clin Exp Ophthalmol. 2012;40(1):48-58. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22003973/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72579"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"502"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17822"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17822"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/06a79121-1ae5-476e-9340-e3acde68e35a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage